# Service Layer

## Responsibility

Services contain business logic and orchestration: validate business rules, coordinate repositories and other services, manage transactions. Controllers and repositories do not contain business logic.

## Structure

- One service per aggregate or use-case area (e.g. `ItemService`, `OrderService`).
- Use `@Service`; inject only repositories and other services via constructor (`@RequiredArgsConstructor` + `final`).
- Methods represent use cases or clear operations: `findById`, `create`, `update`, `placeOrder`, etc.
- Prefer interface + impl only when you need multiple implementations or proxying (e.g. different backends).

## Transactions

- Use `@Transactional` on public methods that modify data; use `@Transactional(readOnly = true)` for read-only methods (performance hint).
- Default rollback on unchecked exceptions; use `rollbackFor` for checked exceptions if you throw them.
- Keep transaction boundaries at service level, not in controllers or repositories.

```java
// ✅ GOOD
@Service
@RequiredArgsConstructor
public class ItemService {
    private final ItemRepository itemRepository;

    @Transactional(readOnly = true)
    public ItemResponse findById(Long id) {
        Item item = itemRepository.findById(id)
            .orElseThrow(() -> new ResourceNotFoundException("Item", id));
        return toResponse(item);
    }

    @Transactional
    public ItemResponse create(CreateItemRequest request) {
        Item item = new Item(request.getName(), request.getPrice());
        return toResponse(itemRepository.save(item));
    }
}
```

## Design

- Services work with entities and DTOs; convert at boundaries (controller ↔ service with DTOs, service ↔ repository with entities).
- Throw domain or app exceptions (e.g. `ResourceNotFoundException`, `ValidationException`); let `@ControllerAdvice` map them to HTTP responses.
- No HTTP or Servlet types in services (no `HttpServletRequest`, `ResponseEntity`); keep layer portable.

## Don’t

- Put HTTP or request/response handling in services.
- Annotate repository interfaces with `@Transactional` for normal CRUD; handle transactions in the service that coordinates the operation.
